Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report for the year 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada take the positions one to three, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe are at the bottom.
(All rankings can be read at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there, among the countries, besides military competition, also an economic competition?
Is there even any sense in saying that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term—that is, over a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of a country simultaneously says anything about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
Nevertheless, it makes sense to create a ranking of countries with regard to their growth potential.
Each country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, in which the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries, for example, compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more foreign direct investment a country can attract, the less another country receives.
This becomes entirely clear when countries compete for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and often countries promote themselves with tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to the curriculum at the local technical university.
This year, we determined a country's competitiveness (growth potential) based on three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we determined indicators, whose average values were calculated using a special method in order to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The technology criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and to utilize technologies developed elsewhere for its own purposes.
Some countries like the United States, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thereby achieve high values in the area of innovation.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovation-friendly countries also enjoy a high level of prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the United States, Canada, and Finland occupy the first three positions on the ranking.
The "public institutions" criterion refers to the quality of governance.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one rely on the government to properly fulfill its obligations?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and decrepit judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are leading worldwide, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers on the ranking.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced state budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans in the capital market, and high confidence that the government fulfills its financial obligations.
From the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth, even if the companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovation-friendly and the non-innovation-friendly.
Only about 20 countries are actively involved in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a superior system of technological innovation is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, government laboratories should be of world-class quality, and government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory education.
In the United States and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed domestically.
Some countries are better at importing new technologies than others.
In the past ten or fifteen years, most technology imports occurred within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the respective economies of the host countries.
Therefore, it made perfect sense for these countries to strive with all vigor to attract these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that occupy the top positions this year, such as the United States or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while other countries ranked further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partly, the slowdown of the economy is linked to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is also becoming increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks had already slipped into a recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe this to be a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the United States will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
